## Pattern Examples: MCP Tool Group Registration (Schedules as canonical template)

---

### Directory Structure

Every tool group lives in its own subdirectory under `src/tools/`:

```
src/tools/workflows/
  index.ts               ← barrel re-exports only
  create-workflow.ts
  update-workflow.ts
  list-workflows.ts
  delete-workflow.ts
  trigger-workflow.ts
```

---

### Pattern 1: Barrel `index.ts`

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/tools/schedules/index.ts:1-5`

One named re-export per tool file, nothing else:

```typescript
export { registerCreateScheduleTool } from "./create-schedule";
export { registerDeleteScheduleTool } from "./delete-schedule";
export { registerListSchedulesTool } from "./list-schedules";
export { registerRunScheduleNowTool } from "./run-schedule-now";
export { registerUpdateScheduleTool } from "./update-schedule";
```

---

### Pattern 2: Tool file structure (create — mutating with validation)

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/tools/schedules/create-schedule.ts:1-236`

Every tool file follows this exact shape:

```typescript
import type { McpServer } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/mcp.js";
import * as z from "zod";
import { createScheduledTask, getAgentById, getScheduledTaskByName } from "@/be/db";
import { createToolRegistrar } from "@/tools/utils";

export const registerCreateScheduleTool = (server: McpServer) => {
  createToolRegistrar(server)(
    "create-schedule",               // ← tool name (kebab-case)
    {
      title: "Create Scheduled Task",
      annotations: { destructiveHint: false },   // or destructiveHint: true, readOnlyHint: true, idempotentHint: true
      description: "...",
      inputSchema: z.object({ ... }),
      outputSchema: z.object({
        yourAgentId: z.string().uuid().optional(),  // ← always present on mutating tools
        success: z.boolean(),
        message: z.string(),
        schedule: z.object({ ... }).optional(),     // ← the created/updated entity, optional
      }),
    },
    async ({ ...args }, requestInfo, _meta) => {
      // 1. Guard: agent ID required
      if (!requestInfo.agentId) {
        return {
          content: [{ type: "text", text: 'Agent ID not found. Set the "X-Agent-ID" header.' }],
          structuredContent: { success: false, message: '...' },
        };
      }

      // 2. Validate inputs (business rules, duplicate checks, FK lookups)

      // 3. try/catch around DB call
      try {
        const entity = createScheduledTask({ ..., createdByAgentId: requestInfo.agentId });
        return {
          content: [{ type: "text", text: `Created schedule "${entity.name}".` }],
          structuredContent: {
            yourAgentId: requestInfo.agentId,
            success: true,
            message: `Created schedule "${entity.name}".`,
            schedule: entity,
          },
        };
      } catch (error) {
        const message = error instanceof Error ? error.message : "Unknown error";
        return {
          content: [{ type: "text", text: `Failed to create schedule: ${message}` }],
          structuredContent: { yourAgentId: requestInfo.agentId, success: false, message: `Failed to create schedule: ${message}` },
        };
      }
    },
  );
};
```

Key structural rules visible in the file:
- Every handler is `async (..., requestInfo, _meta)` — the third param `_meta` is always underscore-prefixed and unused
- Both `content` (text for LLM) and `structuredContent` (typed object for callers) are always returned together
- `content[0].type` is always `"text"`
- `yourAgentId` appears in `structuredContent` on all mutating tools (not on list tools)

---

### Pattern 3: List tool (read-only)

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/tools/schedules/list-schedules.ts:1-106`

Differences from the create pattern:
- `annotations: { readOnlyHint: true }` instead of `destructiveHint`
- No `yourAgentId` in the outputSchema (see line 19 — it IS present but optional; the list tool does include it in the success path at line 83)
- `outputSchema` includes array + `count: z.number()`
- `structuredContent` error path includes `schedules: [], count: 0` to satisfy the schema

```typescript
outputSchema: z.object({
  yourAgentId: z.string().uuid().optional(),
  success: z.boolean(),
  message: z.string(),
  schedules: z.array(z.object({ ... })),
  count: z.number(),
}),
```

Error return for list tools includes empty defaults:
```typescript
structuredContent: {
  success: false,
  message: `Failed to list schedules: ${message}`,
  schedules: [],
  count: 0,
},
```

---

### Pattern 4: Delete tool (authorization check pattern)

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/tools/schedules/delete-schedule.ts:1-127`

The lookup-then-authorize-then-act sequence is identical across delete and update tools:

```typescript
// 1. Lookup by ID or name (both are optional, one required)
const schedule = scheduleId
  ? getScheduledTaskById(scheduleId)
  : name
    ? getScheduledTaskByName(name)
    : null;

if (!schedule) {
  return { content: [{ type: "text", text: "Schedule not found." }],
           structuredContent: { success: false, message: "Schedule not found." } };
}

// 2. Authorization check
const caller = getAgentById(requestInfo.agentId);
const isCreator = schedule.createdByAgentId === requestInfo.agentId;
const isLead = caller?.isLead === true;

if (!isCreator && !isLead) {
  return { content: [{ type: "text", text: "Only the creator or lead can delete this schedule." }],
           structuredContent: { success: false, message: "..." } };
}

// 3. Delete
const deleted = deleteScheduledTask(schedule.id);
```

Delete `outputSchema` returns a trimmed echo of what was deleted:
```typescript
outputSchema: z.object({
  yourAgentId: z.string().uuid().optional(),
  success: z.boolean(),
  message: z.string(),
  deletedSchedule: z.object({ id: z.string(), name: z.string() }).optional(),
}),
```

---

### Pattern 5: Action/trigger tool (run-schedule-now analogue)

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/tools/schedules/run-schedule-now.ts:1-124`

For a "trigger" action (not pure CRUD), the pattern is identical but the handler calls a service function instead of a DB function, then re-fetches to get the updated state:

```typescript
await runScheduleNow(schedule.id);                    // service call (async)
const updated = getScheduledTaskById(schedule.id);    // re-fetch for fresh state

return {
  content: [{ type: "text", text: `Executed schedule "${schedule.name}". ...` }],
  structuredContent: {
    yourAgentId: requestInfo.agentId,
    success: true,
    message: `Executed schedule "${schedule.name}".`,
    schedule: updated ? { id: updated.id, name: updated.name, nextRunAt: updated.nextRunAt } : undefined,
  },
};
```

---

### Pattern 6: DB layer — types and CRUD functions

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/be/db.ts:3890-4152`

Three types per entity, always private `Row` → public domain type via mapper:

```
ScheduledTaskRow       (private, SQLite raw — nulls, number for booleans, JSON strings)
ScheduledTask          (public domain type, defined in src/types.ts via z.infer<>)
CreateScheduledTaskData  (exported interface for insert)
UpdateScheduledTaskData  (exported interface for partial update)
ScheduledTaskFilters     (exported interface for list filters)
```

**`ScheduledTaskRow` → `ScheduledTask` mapper** (`db.ts:3914`):
- `null` → `undefined` via `?? undefined`
- `number` (0/1) → `boolean` via `=== 1`
- JSON string → array via `JSON.parse`
- enum cast: `row.model as "haiku" | "sonnet" | "opus" | null`

**Domain type** lives in `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/types.ts:356-384` as a Zod schema + `z.infer<>`:

```typescript
export const ScheduledTaskSchema = z.object({ ... });
export type ScheduledTask = z.infer<typeof ScheduledTaskSchema>;
```

**INSERT pattern** (`db.ts:3998`): Uses `RETURNING *` + `.get()` to return the created row in one statement, throws if `!row`.

**UPDATE pattern** (`db.ts:4055`): Builds `updates: string[]` and `params` arrays dynamically — only fields that are `!== undefined` are included. Always appends `lastUpdatedAt = ?` as the final SET clause. Uses `RETURNING *` + `.get()`.

**DELETE pattern** (`db.ts:4149`): Uses `.run()` and checks `result.changes > 0` for boolean return.

**List pattern** (`db.ts:3945`): Builds query string with `WHERE 1=1` + conditional `AND` clauses, uses `.all(...params).map(rowToScheduledTask)`.

---

### Pattern 7: Server registration

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/server.ts:40-47, 162-169`

Import from the barrel, register inside a capability guard block:

```typescript
// src/server.ts

// Import block (top of file, grouped by capability with a comment)
// Scheduling capability
import {
  registerCreateScheduleTool,
  registerDeleteScheduleTool,
  registerListSchedulesTool,
  registerRunScheduleNowTool,
  registerUpdateScheduleTool,
} from "./tools/schedules";

// Registration block (inside createServer(), with matching comment)
// Scheduling capability - scheduled task management
if (hasCapability("scheduling")) {
  registerListSchedulesTool(server);
  registerCreateScheduleTool(server);
  registerUpdateScheduleTool(server);
  registerDeleteScheduleTool(server);
  registerRunScheduleNowTool(server);
}
```

The capability string is also added to `DEFAULT_CAPABILITIES` at line 72:
```typescript
const DEFAULT_CAPABILITIES = "core,task-pool,messaging,profiles,services,scheduling,epics,memory";
```

---

### Pattern 8: `tool-config.ts` — DEFERRED_TOOLS registration

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/tools/tool-config.ts:41-48`

New tool groups go into `DEFERRED_TOOLS` (not `CORE_TOOLS`). The schedules block shows the exact comment + grouping convention:

```typescript
export const DEFERRED_TOOLS = new Set([
  // Scheduling (5)
  "list-schedules",
  "create-schedule",
  "update-schedule",
  "delete-schedule",
  "run-schedule-now",

  // Epics (7)
  "create-epic",
  // ...
]);
```

Format: `// GroupName (count)` comment followed by the tool name strings.

---

### Pattern 9: `createToolRegistrar` helper

**Found in**: `/Users/taras/Documents/code/agent-swarm/src/tools/utils.ts:86-115`

`createToolRegistrar(server)` returns a function that wraps `server.registerTool`. It:
1. Extracts `requestInfo` (sessionId + agentId from `X-Agent-ID` header) from MCP meta
2. Injects it as the second argument to the tool callback

The exported type `RequestInfo` (line 18) is what every tool receives as `requestInfo`:
```typescript
export type RequestInfo = {
  sessionId: string | undefined;
  agentId: string | undefined;
};
```

---

### End-to-end CRUD flow summary

```
Tool file (src/tools/workflows/create-workflow.ts)
  └─ createToolRegistrar(server)("create-workflow", { inputSchema, outputSchema }, handler)
       └─ handler receives (args, requestInfo, _meta)
            └─ calls createWorkflow(data) from src/be/db.ts
                 └─ INSERT ... RETURNING * → .get() → rowToWorkflow(row)
                      └─ returns Workflow (domain type from src/types.ts)
            └─ returns { content: [{type:"text", text:"..."}], structuredContent: { success, message, workflow } }

Barrel (src/tools/workflows/index.ts)
  └─ export { registerCreateWorkflowTool } from "./create-workflow"

server.ts
  └─ import { registerCreateWorkflowTool, ... } from "./tools/workflows"
  └─ if (hasCapability("workflows")) { registerCreateWorkflowTool(server); ... }
  └─ DEFAULT_CAPABILITIES += ",workflows"

tool-config.ts
  └─ DEFERRED_TOOLS.add("create-workflow", "list-workflows", ...)

types.ts
  └─ export const WorkflowSchema = z.object({ ... })
  └─ export type Workflow = z.infer<typeof WorkflowSchema>
```

