**OpenRouter provider** (primary): Uses Vercel AI SDK (`ai` package) with `@ai-sdk/openai` pointed at OpenRouter's base URL. Supports `generateObject()` with Zod schema for structured output. Fast (<1s), no subprocess.

**Claude CLI provider** (fallback): Spawns `claude -p --model haiku --json-schema '...'` — converts Zod schema to JSON Schema dict via `zodToJsonSchema()`. Already has a precedent in `hook.ts:1011` for one-shot Claude invocations. Slower (~2-5s) but works with OAuth tokens when no API key is available.

**Codebase context**: No Anthropic SDK, Vercel AI SDK, or OpenRouter integration exists today. The `openai` npm package is used only for embeddings. `--json-schema` is not used anywhere yet. This will be the first direct chat/completion API integration.

**Rationale**: The Zod-based `query<T>()` interface is generic enough for any structured output need (classification, extraction, etc.), not just category routing. OpenRouter gives model flexibility (use cheap/fast models for classification). Claude CLI fallback ensures it works even without an API key.

#### 4. Execution Model — fire-and-forget async BFS with workflow run tracking

**Decision**: Synchronous BFS walk inside an async function, fired without blocking the trigger source. Each execution creates a `workflow_runs` row. Tasks created by workflows are tagged with `workflowRunId`. No external queue — the DB is the execution log and recovery mechanism.

```sql
CREATE TABLE workflow_runs (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  workflowId TEXT NOT NULL REFERENCES workflows(id),
  status TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'running' CHECK(status IN ('running', 'completed', 'failed')),
  triggerData TEXT,     -- JSON: the event that triggered the run
  context TEXT,         -- JSON: accumulated node outputs
  error TEXT,
  startedAt TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now')),
  finishedAt TEXT
);

CREATE TABLE workflow_run_steps (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  runId TEXT NOT NULL REFERENCES workflow_runs(id),
  nodeId TEXT NOT NULL,
  nodeType TEXT NOT NULL,
  status TEXT NOT NULL CHECK(status IN ('running', 'completed', 'failed', 'skipped')),
  input TEXT,           -- JSON
  output TEXT,          -- JSON
  error TEXT,
  executedAt TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))
);
```

Tasks created by workflow actions get a `workflowRunId` column on `agent_tasks` (new FK) so you can trace "this task was created by workflow run X."

**Execution pattern**:

```typescript
async function onTrigger(workflow: Workflow, triggerData: unknown) {
  // Fire and forget — do NOT await
  runWorkflowExecution(workflow, triggerData).catch((err) => {
    logger.error("Workflow execution failed", { err, workflowId: workflow.id });
  });
}

async function runWorkflowExecution(wf: Workflow, data: unknown) {
  const runId = createId();
  await db.createWorkflowRun(runId, wf.id, 'running', data);
  try {
    const ctx = { trigger: data };
    // BFS walk...
    for each node: execute, log step, accumulate context
    await db.updateWorkflowRun(runId, 'completed');
  } catch (err) {
    await db.updateWorkflowRun(runId, 'failed', String(err));
  }
}
```

**No queue needed**. Research confirmed that n8n (regular mode), go-workflows, and Netflix Maestro all use the DB as the source of truth — not an external queue. For crash recovery, a startup sweep finds `workflow_runs` stuck in `'running'` older than 5 minutes and re-executes them.

**Retry handling**: At the node executor level, not the engine level. LLM calls get `withRetry(fn, maxAttempts=3)` with exponential backoff. Structural failures fail the whole run.

**Rationale**: Workflows are short-lived (classify → create task). Fire-and-forget keeps triggers non-blocking. The `workflow_runs` + `workflow_run_steps` tables give full debuggability without queue complexity. If concurrency becomes a concern later, an in-memory semaphore can throttle concurrent executions.

#### 5. Event Bus — abstract interface, in-process `EventEmitter` for v1

**Decision**: Internal event bus with a pluggable interface. v1 uses Node.js `EventEmitter` (available in Bun). Interface designed so Redis pub/sub can be swapped in later without changing event producers or consumers.

```typescript
// src/workflows/event-bus.ts
interface WorkflowEventBus {
  emit(event: string, data: unknown): void;
  on(pattern: string, handler: (data: unknown) => void): void;
  off(pattern: string, handler: (data: unknown) => void): void;
}

// v1: in-process EventEmitter with glob matching
class InProcessEventBus implements WorkflowEventBus { ... }

// Future: Redis pub/sub
// class RedisEventBus implements WorkflowEventBus { ... }
```

Existing handlers emit events after their current logic:

```typescript
// In src/github/handlers.ts, after createTaskExtended():
workflowEventBus.emit('github.pull_request.opened', { repo, number, title, body, ... });

// In src/be/db.ts, after createTaskExtended():
workflowEventBus.emit('task.created', { taskId, source, tags, agentId, ... });

// In src/be/db.ts, after completeTask():
workflowEventBus.emit('task.completed', { taskId, output, agentId, ... });
```

The workflow engine subscribes on startup and checks for matching enabled workflows.

**Rationale**: Clean separation — existing code just emits events. Workflow logic is isolated in `src/workflows/`. The abstract interface costs nothing now but makes Redis/NATS migration trivial later.

#### 6. Node Type Set for v1

**Decision**: Start with all proposed types plus `trigger-email` and `trigger-task-completed`.

**Trigger nodes** (entry points — nodes with no incoming edges):
| Type | Config | Fires when |
|---|---|---|
| `trigger-new-task` | `matchTags`, `matchSource`, `matchTaskType` | Task created matching criteria |
| `trigger-task-completed` | `matchTags`, `matchAgentId` | Task completes matching criteria |
| `trigger-webhook` | (none — workflow ID in URL) | HTTP POST to `/api/workflows/:id/trigger` |
| `trigger-email` | `matchInbox`, `matchSenderDomain` | AgentMail message received matching criteria |
| `trigger-slack-message` | `matchChannel`, `matchPattern` | Slack message matching criteria |
| `trigger-github-event` | `matchEventType`, `matchRepo` | GitHub webhook event matching criteria |

**Condition nodes** (routing — multiple output ports):
| Type | Config | Output Ports |
|---|---|---|
| `llm-classify` | `prompt`, `categories`, `model`, `fallbackPort` | One port per category string |
| `property-match` | `conditions` (array of field/op/value) | `"true"`, `"false"` |
| `code-match` | `code` (JS function string), `outputPorts` | Named ports from `outputPorts` array |

**Action nodes** (outputs — single `"default"` output port for chaining):
| Type | Config | Effect |
|---|---|---|
| `create-task` | `template`, `agentId`, `tags`, `source`, `priority` | Calls `createTaskExtended()` |
| `send-message` | `channelId` or `slackChannel`, `template` | Posts message to channel or Slack |
| `delegate-to-agent` | `agentId`, `taskTemplate`, `offerMode` | Offers/assigns task to specific agent |

Templates in action node configs support mustache-style interpolation from the workflow context: `{{trigger.body.title}}`, `{{nodeId.output.category}}`.

**`code-match` sandbox**: The JS function runs in an isolated scope with no access to `require`, `import`, `process`, `Bun`, or `globalThis`. Input is the workflow context object. Output must be a string matching one of the declared `outputPorts`, or a boolean (mapped to `"true"`/`"false"`).

**Rationale**: This set covers the core use cases — triage new tasks by content, route GitHub events by type, classify emails, and trigger follow-ups when tasks complete. The `code-match` node provides an escape hatch for complex conditions without needing LLM calls.

